25|$|In the 1930s, the Japanese economy {{suffered}} {{less from}} the Great Depression than most <b>industrialized</b> <b>nations,</b> its GDP expanding at the rapid rate of 5% per year. Manufacturing and mining came {{to account for}} more than 30% of GDP, more than twice the value for the agricultural sector. Most industrial growth, however, was geared toward expanding the nation's military power.|$|E
